problems.statement:
Suppose $\{f_n\}$, $\{g_n\}$ are defined on $E$, and
\begin{itemize}
\item[(a)] $\sum f_n$ has uniformly bounded partial sums;
\item[(b)] $g_n \to 0$ uniformly on $E$;
\item[(c)] $g_1(x) \geq g_2(x) \geq g_3(x) \geq \cdots$ for every $x \in E$.
\end{itemize}
Prove that $\sum f_n g_n$ converges uniformly on $E$. \textit{Hint}: Compare with Theorem 3.42.

Assume that $\{f_n\}$ is a sequence of monotonically increasing functions on $R^1$ with $0 \leq f_n(x) \leq 1$ for all $x$ and all $n$.
\begin{itemize}
\item[(a)] Prove that there is a function $f$ and a sequence $\{n_k\}$ such that
$$f(x) = \lim_{k \to \infty} f_{n_k}(x)$$
for every $x \in R^1$. (The existence of such a pointwise convergent subsequence is usually called \textit{Helly's selection theorem}.)
\item[(b)] If, moreover, $f$ is continuous, prove that $f_{n_k} \to f$ uniformly on compact sets.
\end{itemize}
\textit{Hint}: (i) Some subsequence $\{f_{n_i}\}$ converges at all rational points $r$, say, to $f(r)$. (ii) Define $f(x)$, for any $x \in R^1$, to be $\sup f(r)$, the sup being taken over all $r \leq x$. (iii) Show that $f_{n_i}(x) \to f(x)$ at every $x$ at which $f$ is continuous. (This is where monotonicity is strongly used.) (iv) A subsequence of $\{f_{n_i}\}$ converges at every point of discontinuity of $f$ since there are at most countably many such points. This proves (a). To prove (b), modify your proof of (iii) appropriately.

Put $f(0, 0) = 0$, and
$$f(x, y) = \frac{xy(x^2 - y^2)}{x^2 + y^2}$$
if $(x, y) \neq (0, 0)$. Prove that

(a) $f$, $D_1 f$, $D_2 f$ are continuous in $R^2$;

(b) $D_{12} f$ and $D_{21} f$ exist at every point of $R^2$, and are continuous except at $(0, 0)$;

(c) $(D_{12} f)(0, 0) = 1$, and $(D_{21} f)(0, 0) = -1$.
